SECTION 1 — CRITICAL BUG FIX: Russian/Ukrainian Ja→Ya post-processing
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

File to modify: src/pipeline/transliteration_engine.py

After every call to the `transliterate` library for Russian (ru) or Ukrainian (uk),
apply a deterministic post-processing substitution function BEFORE returning the result.
The function must be named `_apply_bgn_pcgn_corrections(text: str) -> str`.

Substitutions to apply (order matters — apply in this sequence):
  "Ja"  → "Ya"    (handles Я at word-initial and post-vowel)
  "ja"  → "ya"
  "Ju"  → "Yu"    (handles Ю)
  "ju"  → "yu"
  "Je"  → "Ye"    (handles Е in word-initial position)
  "je"  → "ye"
  "Shh" → "Shch"  (handles Щ — library outputs Shh, BGN/PCGN mandates Shch)
  "shh" → "shch"

Important: these substitutions must only be applied to Russian/Ukrainian results.
Do NOT apply them to Bulgarian (bg) — Bulgarian has different BGN conventions.

Tests to write in tests/test_transliteration.py:
  - Наталья → NATALYA (not NATALJA)
  - Юрий → YURII (not JURII)  
  - Екатерина → YEKATERINA
  - Татьяна → TATYANA
  - Щукин → SHCHUKHIN (not SHHUKHIN)
  - Verify Bulgarian is NOT affected by these substitutions



